# Coding conventions

## Python (bridge + brain)

- Target Python 3.10+. Use type hints on public functions and dataclasses/pydantic for structured data.
- Keep **`autobot/robot/` dependency-light** (stdlib + the web deps only). The whole app runs on a Pi.
- The app uses `fastapi`, `uvicorn`, `httpx`, `pydantic` (+ optional `paho-mqtt`); avoid heavy vendor AI
  SDKs — talk HTTP to the provider.
- Comments explain **why / trade-offs / constraints**, never restate the code. (Mirrors the upstream
  bridge and GrowBot style — terse, high-signal comments.)
- Fail soft: wrap subsystem calls so one failure (audio, eyes, provider) never takes down the loop.
- No secrets, API keys, or full credential blobs in logs.

## TypeScript / React (webui)

- TypeScript everywhere. Functional components + hooks. Tailwind for styling (no ad-hoc CSS files beyond
  the single `index.css` with Tailwind directives).
- All server access goes through `src/api.ts`. Components never `fetch` directly.
- Keep the UI a thin client: no robot logic in the browser, just rendering + control intents.

## C (ebo_bridge.c)

- Keep it a single file, no libc-heavy abstractions; it's run under the Android linker on the Pi.
- Any new control `kind` must be documented in `docs/BRIDGE_PROTOCOL.md` and mirrored in `native_link.py`.

## General

- Match the surrounding file's style. Small, reviewable changes. Update the relevant `docs/` file in the
  same change as the code. When in doubt, read `AGENTS.md`.
